It's because of this (quoting from Xianin's paste half way down):
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Sophia Stewart wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">"The reason you have not seen any of this in the media is because Warner Brothers parent company is AOL-Time Warner... this GIANT owns 95 percent of the media... let me give you a clue as to what they own in the media business... New York Times papers/magazines, LA Times papers/magazines, People Magazine, CNN news, Extra, Celebrity Justice, Entertainment Tonight, HBO, New Line Cinema, Dreamworks, Newsweek, Village Roadshow... many, many more!... They are not going to report on themselves. They have been surpressing my case for years..."</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I personally didn't know of this either. Cannot believe a prestigious business such as Warner Brothers (there needs to be greater ramifications for plagarism at schools so as to prevent these cases happening to future generations) would actually do something such as this. But it makes absolute sense listening to the author talk about her own work because of the vindicative way in which she spoke about the book's intent.
<br />

<br />
However, I do not believe her intention was solely to "awaken" people as she claims thus. She was just unable to sell her novel well enough to the public originally. She may or may not be a good writer because the success that was the original Matrix was mostly due to Hollywood's special effects. I highly doubt any of us here would be interested in a possibly poorly written (again this isn't my opinion, but rather a mere assumption based on her book not selling much) story of how some guy is the god incarnate and some other bald bloke is convinced that the savior has truly arrived even though He himself isn't all that interested at first. 
<br />

<br />
But she had an original idea (unlike Terry Brooks...that piece of crap of an author. I flame him at every opportunity for I deemed The Sword of Shanarra as a poorly written trilogy with flawed character development [even by Salvatore's standards] and his attempts at action are neither vivid nor picturesque) and the (first) movie was great. Perhaps I will read her book if I can find it.
<br />

<br />
And I constrain no envy towards her...she got exploited and right is being done to her.
<br />

<br />
This does call for a "goodjob" to WB...people think of them quite lowly now.<br />
